    <div id=3D"pu97_view" class=3D"cms_unit cms_row col-12 col-md-12 ">
    <div class=3D"">
            <span id=3D"pu97"></span>

                        <div class=3D"cms_text">1 tesla is therefore one ne=
wton per ampere and metre.
This means that 1 tesla is equivalent to the magnetic flux density that exe=
rts exactly 1 newton of <a href=3D"https://www.supermagnete.de/eng/magnetis=
m/Magnetic-forces-forces-of-attraction-forces-of-repulsion">attractive forc=
e</a>
on a 1-metre-long conductor through which 1 ampere of current flows (due to=
 the magnetic effect of the current in the conductor).</div><div class=3D"c=
ms_text"><br>
The magnetic field strength <i>H</i>
can be determined from the magnetic flux density <i>B</i>.
To do so, the magnetic flux density <i>B</i>
must be divided by the <a href=3D"https://www.supermagnete.de/eng/magnetism=
/Permeability">permeability</a>
of the material <i>=CE=BC</i>
and the permeability of the vacuum <i>=CE=BC<sub>0</sub></i>:</div><div cla=
ss=3D"cms_text"><br>
<span><span class=3D"katex"><span class=3D"katex-mathml"><math xmlns=3D"htt=
p://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>=3D</mo><mf=
rac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>=CE=BC</mi><msub><mi>=CE=BC</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></=
mrow></mfrac><mo>=E2=8B=85</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=3D"app=
lication/x-tex">
H =3D \frac{1}{\mu\mu_0}\cdot {B}</annotation></semantics></math></span><sp=
an class=3D"katex-html" aria-hidden=3D"true"><span class=3D"base"><span cla=
